<HEADLINE> Chinese Film Wins Venice Film Festival's Golden Lion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 11 (Xinhua) -- "Not One Less," a film by
Chinese director Zhang Yimou, won the Golden Lion award at the
56th Venice film festival Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
Zhang, who won a Golden Lion seven years ago for the film "The
story of Qiu Ju," this time hit the mark with the story of a
13-year old school teacher in rural China who has to go and find a
missing pupil.
</P>
<P>
The film, which used real people instead of actors, was the
result of Zhang's long-cherished desire to make a film about
children in China's schools.
</P>
<P>
"I hope that all children can have a happy childhood," he said
as he received the award.
</P>
<P>
The Jury's special prize meanwhile went to "The Wind Will Carry
Us" (Le Vent Nous Emportera) by Iranian film-maker Abbas
Kiarostami, who also won an award in Cannes.
</P>
<P>
His film, like Zhang Yimou's, was set in a rural part of his
country and used local villagers in the cast. It revolves around a
group of people searching for something that is never made clear.
</P>
<P>
Giovanni Davide Maderna won the best first film prize for "This
is the Garden" (Questo e' il Giardino).
</P>
<P>
Britain's Jim Broadbent took best actor for his performance in
Mike Leigh's Topsy Turvy and France's Natalie Baye, co-star in "A
Pornographic Liaison" (Une Liaison Pornographique) was chosen as
best actress. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
