<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OPEC President Arrives in UAE for Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, September 11 (Xinhua) -- President of the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) Youcef Yousfi
arrived here Saturday on a two-day visit to the United Arab
Emirates (UAE).
</P>
<P>
The visit is part of a tour of Gulf Arab oil-producing states
by the OPEC chief ahead of the group's upcoming ministerial
meeting in Vienna.
</P>
<P>
Yousfi, who is also Algeria's energy and mines minister, will
hold talks with UAE Minister of Petroleum and Mineral Resources
Obeid Bin Saif Al Nasir on a number of oil issues, notably the
continuation of OPEC's policy of output reduction that has been in
place since March.
</P>
<P>
In a statement to the official WAM news agency, he expressed
the hope that the March output cut agreement would last until
March 2000.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, OPEC members and major oil producers
outside the organization cut output by 2.1 million barrels per
day.
</P>
<P>
"There is a significant improvement in oil prices following
compliance with the agreement, but I share the opinion of some
OPEC members that the world oil stockpile is still high and there
should be some balance," Yousfi said.
</P>
<P>
On reports that there had been proposals to establish both a
price and output ceilings, he said the issue was subject to the
approval of OPEC member states. 
</P>
</TEXT>
