<HEADLINE> New Political Party Launched In Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 11 (Xinhua) -- A new political party, the
Movement for Democratic Change (MDC), was officially launched on
Saturday at Harare's Rufaro Stadium.
</P>
<P>
In his inaugural speech, Interim President of the MDC Gibson
Sibanda, who is also president of the Zimbabwe Congress of Trade
Unions (ZCTU), said time had come when people of Zimbabwe should
take charge of their lives and future through political change.
</P>
<P>
He said the ruling Zimbabwe African National Union (Patriotic
Front) (ZANU-PF) and its government had taken people for granted
for so long while turning a deaf ear to suggestions put to them by
the ZCTU and other groups representing the workers.
</P>
<P>
"We live in an economy that is not able to satisfy even the
basic needs of most Zimbabweans, where most people face a
continuous downward slide in job opportunities, income, food
security and well being. Business has collapsed and poverty has
grown," he said.
</P>
<P>
Among 15,000 people attending the rally were worker
representatives from all over the country.
</P>
<P>
Another MDC leader Morgan Tsvangirai, who is also ZCTU
Secretary-General, said the MDC will give immediate priorities to
restoration of economic stability and growth, job creation, land
reform and building an accountable, transparent and open
government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
