<HEADLINE> Annan Sees Shift in Indonesia's Stance on Outside Help </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 11 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan said Saturday Indonesia seems to have softened its
position towards the proposed international help to improve the
security in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters here that he made the judgement based on what
the Indonesian military chief General Wiranto said and called it
an encouragement.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian Defense Minister was quoted as saying Saturday
that he saw a multi-national peace-keeping force as an option to
resolve the security problem in East Timor, the former Portuguese
colony annexed in 1976 by Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
He would report his idea to President B.J. Habibie for him to
consider, Wiranto said in Dili, East Timor capital where he was
accompanying a U.N. Security Council mission to visit the
territory.
</P>
<P>
But until Friday, Wiranto and other government officials had
insisted that it was not the right time for an international
force to land in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
Annan said he will call Habibie Sunday morning to hear directly
from him what the Indonesian position is.
</P>
<P>
In the Security Council, an open debate was going on Saturday
while awaiting the report from the five-member council mission,
expected to return Monday.
</P>
<P>
Annan said Friday that "The time has clearly come" for
Indonesia to accept "without further delay" the international help
by a number of countries led by Australia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
