<HEADLINE> GCC FMs Welcome New Palestinian-Israeli Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Foreign ministers of the
Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) states welcomed on Saturday the
new Israeli-Palestinian peace agreement signed last week in the
Egyptian Red Sea resort of Sharm El-Sheikh.
</P>
<P>
In a final communique issued at the conclusion of their
two-day meeting in the Saudi Red Sea port city of Jeddah,
the ministers expressed hope that the Israeli government would
fully and precisely implement the agreement.
</P>
<P>
According to the modified Wye River accord, which was
signed by Palestinian National Authority Chairman Yasser Arafat
and Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak, Israel will withdraw
its troops from 7 percent of the West Bank and release the
first of 350 Palestinian security prisoners.
</P>
<P>
The implementation of the accord will pave the way for
talks on a permanent peace settlement, the Kuwait News Agency
quoted the communique as saying.
</P>
<P>
The GCC foreign ministers also asserted their full support
for Syria in its call to resume negotiations with Israel from
the point they last stopped, as well as its rights to
regain the Golan Heights, which is now occupied by Israel.
</P>
<P>
The GCC officials also underlined the importance of Israel's
unconditional withdrawal from south Lebanon according to related
United Nations' resolutions.
</P>
<P>
The GCC, a regional political and economic alliance
established in 1981, comprises Bahrain, Kuwait, Oman, Qatar,
Saudi Arabia and the United Arab Emirates (UAE). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
