<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt to Continue Investigations into Lax Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Investigations into the lax
security allowing a man to attack and injure President Hosni
Mubarak Monday will extend into the highest levels of the security
apparatus, the Egyptian interior minister said on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Investigations have been conducted into the lack of sufficient
awareness and quick response of the officers responsible for
securing the Mubarak's route, Habib el-Adli told an emergency
meeting of the parliament's Defense and National Security Council.
</P>
<P>
The security forces should have "suspected this person" and
taken the necessary steps to prevent their security cordon from
being penetrated, el-Adli was quoted as saying by Egypt's Middle
East News Agency.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, Said Hassan Soliman was shot dead by guards after
slightly wounding Mubarak with a knife when the president was
riding to a meeting in the Mediterranean port city of Port Said,
180 kilometers northeast of Cairo.
</P>
<P>
After the attack, Egypt's intelligence chief Lt. Gen. Hani
el-Azabi was dismissed and transferred to the post of border
security chief.
</P>
<P>
Three other top security officials in Port Said were also
transferred to new posts and were referred to a disciplinary
committee on charges of gross negligence.
</P>
<P>
If convicted by the disciplinary board, they could face
dismissal and revocation of pension and benefits.
</P>
<P>
Similar charges have also been leveled against another 14
officers of various ranks who failed in carrying out their duties,
el-Adli told the committee members.
</P>
<P>
He said the attack on Mubarak was "an individual act blamed on
a person suffering from mental disorder." The attacker "was
diagnosed four years ago as schizophrenic and mentally disorder."
</P>
<P>
There has been no information to show that the attacker has
affiliation with any outlawed group, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the daily Al-Ahram published Thursday,
Mubarak blamed the attack on lax security. He singled out the
three Port Said security heads, and said he will order security
reviews in all areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
