<HEADLINE> HIV Infection Soars in Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 11 (Xinhua) -- The number of carriers of HIV,
the virus that causes AIDS, soared by 70 percent in the first
eight months of this year in Russia, Health Minister Yuri
Shevchenko said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"Residents of Moscow and the Moscow region account for the
unprecedented growth in the HIV infection," the Interfax news
agency quoted Shevchenko as saying.
</P>
<P>
Shevchenko did not specify how many HIV carriers were
registered during the period.
</P>
<P>
"HIV hit the circle of the capital's drug users and the
infection sky-rocketed," the minister said.
</P>
<P>
"These scary figures would have been even more frightening if a
net of anti-AIDS organizations had not been created and had not
functioned reliably," he said.
</P>
<P>
A total of 83 territorial and 6 regional anti-AIDS centers
operate in Russia, along with over 1,000 test laboratories and 250
offices for anonymous examination, the minister said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
