<DOCNO> XIE19990912.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two Suspects Arrested in Moscow Building Blast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 11 (Xinhua) -- The Russian Federal Security
Service (FSB) said Saturday that it had detained two suspects
following a blast in a Moscow apartment building that killed 94
people and injured more than 100 others.
</P>
<P>
Investigators are still trying to pinpoint the causes of the
blast that ripped through the nine-story building early Thursday
in southeast Moscow, although they have found traces of an
explosive often used by guerrilla groups at the site.
</P>
<P>
It was unclear whether the blast was a terrorist act or caused
by mishandling of illegally stored explosives.
</P>
<P>
The FSB, the successor to the Soviet KGB, said the suspects,
whose identity was not revealed, were being interviewed and would
stay in custody at least until Monday.
</P>
<P>
Police have been investigating a link between the blast and the
owners of a shop on the ground floor of the block.
</P>
<P>
Security officials have not ruled out a possible connection
between the blast and violence in the southern region of
Daghestan, where Russian troops are fighting Islamic rebels.
</P>
<P>
A car bomb explosion at a military apartment block in the
Daghestani town of Buinaksk killed 64 people last weekend. Three
suspects were detained in the blast believed to be staged by
Islamic militants.
</P>
<P>
On August 31, one woman died and dozens of people were injured
in a bomb blast at the Manezh shopping mall near the Kremlin. No
one claimed responsibility for that attack. 
</P>
</TEXT>
