<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Congolese Rebels Urged to Sort out Differences </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 11 (Xinhua) -- South Africa Saturday
urged rival rebel factions in the war-torn Democratic Republic of
the Congo (DRC) to sort out their differences by themselves.
</P>
<P>
It was perhaps time for them to settle their own quarrels
without outside help, Foreign Affairs Minister Nkosazana Zuma told
reporters in Pretoria.
</P>
<P>
"Maybe it's high time they start deciding themselves as
Congolese rather than expecting other people all the time to come
in and say this must happen," she said, hinting at south africa's
growing impatience with the inability of the rival factions to end
their conflict.
</P>
<P>
Zuma has played a key role in making the Congolese Rally for
Democracy (RCD) rebels to sign a ceasefire deal after internal
rivalry delayed their endorsement of the accord for about six
weeks.
</P>
<P>
The two RCD factions are currently at odds over who should
represent the movement in the joint military commission which is
overseeing the ceasefire.
</P>
<P>
Leaders from both factions held separate talks with the South
African government last weekend.
</P>
<P>
Zuma said on Saturday South Africa used these discussions to
urge the two groups to settle their differences.
</P>
<P>
"We thought it could be a beginning for them as Congolese
deciding for themselves how they should be represented, and that
other people should only be brought in if they fail to resolve the
matter," she said, adding that "we are still waiting for them."
</P>
<P>
Asked if the two factions should not be seen as two different
movements, she said the RCD had signed the ceasefire as a single
entity.
</P>
<P>
"That is why there is now a problem with representation. The
RCD should tell us whether they are now one or two movements," she
said.
</P>
<P>
Zuma said South Africa was optimistic that the conflict in the
central African country would be resolved.
</P>
<P>
"I think people are committed. There is a goodwill, although
trust still has to be built."
</P>
<P>
She stressed that South Africa did not favor a particular
political grouping in the DRC, and would be prepared to hold talks
with any of the parties involved in peace process.
</P>
<P>
South Africa's involvement was aimed at enabling the Congolese
to determine their own fate through a process of national
political dialogue, she said.
</P>
<P>
"We must get the DRC to move away from being a country based on
ethnic rivalry because such an approach will not bring stability,"
she said.
</P>
<P>
The emphasis should be put on drawing up a framework or
constitution on how the DRC should be run, so that it became less
important who was running the country, Zuma said.
</P>
<P>
The RCD signed the ceasefire text on August 31 in Lusaka,
Zambia, adding their signatures to those of another rebel group
and the six countries that were involved in the year-long war.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe, Namibia and Angola have been fighting on the side of
the DRC President Laurent Kabila against rebel forces intent on
toppling him.
</P>
<P>
The rebels received military backing from Rwanda and Uganda.
</P>
<P>
The accord provides a ceasefire, the creation of a united army
after a 90-day dialogue on the DRC's political future, and
international peacekeepers to monitor compliance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
