<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Vows to Reduce Illiteracy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Education Minister Kader
Asmal Saturday pledged greater efforts to reduce illiteracy in
South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Asmal said in a speech that a total of 3.2 million adult South
Africans did not have any schooling, while another 9.4 million did
not complete grade 9.
</P>
<P>
"Thus, 12.6 million or 54 percent of the total adult population
have not completed a general level of education," he told an adult
literacy awards ceremony in Pretoria.
</P>
<P>
Budgetary constraints has resulted in several provincial
education departments cutting back or closing adult basic
education and training programs.
</P>
<P>
"This trend ought to be reversed, but it is improbable that the
 government will find sufficient additional funds in the near
future to eliminate illiteracy through formal programs run by
provincial education departments," the minister said.
</P>
<P>
He called on businesses and other donors to help fund adult
literacy programs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
