<HEADLINE> Russia's Chechnya Extends Emergency Rule </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Chechen President Aslan
Maskhadov on Saturday issued a decree to extend the state of
emergency in the Russian republic, the Interfax news agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
"I had to extend the emergency rule and announce a general
draft of all male adults," Interfax quoted Maskhadov as saying at
a press conference in Grozny, capital of the breakaway republic in
southern Russia.
</P>
<P>
The state of emergency, originally set at one-month, was last
declared on August 16, about one week after Chechen rebels sneaked
into Daghestan, another Russian republic bordering Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
Russia's federal forces have since launched a campaign to root
out the Islamic militants and hinted at the time that military
strikes against the rebels could be extended to inside Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
After their defeat following a two-week federal campaign, the
rebels launched a second wave of attacks in another region of
Daghestan on September 5.
</P>
<P>
Federal military and interior forces are intensifying their
assault on the rebels in the past week. Chechnya repeatedly
accused the federal troops of bombing its territory, but Moscow
denied the accusations.
</P>
<P>
Maskhadov said he was taking "all possible and impossible
political steps to prevent a large-scale war and restore peace
around Chechnya and the region at large."
</P>
<P>
A meeting with Russian President Boris Yeltsin could become one
of these steps, Maskhadov said.
</P>
<P>
In 1991, shortly before the collapse of the Soviet Union,
Chechnya declared itself an independent state. The Russian
government refused to recognize Chechnya's independence, and in
December 1994 federal troops moved into the republic.
</P>
<P>
Fighting between federal and Chechen forces continued into
1996. In August of that year, Chechen rebel leaders signed a broad
agreement with the Russian government, bringing an end to the war.
</P>
<P>
The agreement called for the immediate withdrawal of Russian
forces and the postponement of a decision on Chechnya's political
status until December 2001. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
