<HEADLINE> S. Leonean Rebels Still Holding 1,000 Children: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Rebels in Sierra Leone are
still holding about 1,000 of the 4,000 children they abducted
during their invasion of the country's capital Freetown in January
this year, a United Nations official was quoted as saying on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Olara Otunnu, the U.N. special representative on children in
armed conflict, said that about 60 percent of the abducted
children were girls. Most of them were being sexually abused, the
Pan-African News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Otunnu, who returned from a six-day visit to Sierra Leone on
September 4, said that more than 10,000 children in the country
have been serving as child soldiers with the rebels and civil
militia.
</P>
<P>
In a 15-point agenda, he called for the establishment of a
national commission in the country to promote the rights and
welfare of children after the war.
</P>
<P>
Otunnu appealed to all political leaders in Sierra Leone to
demonstrate their commitment to implementing the peace accord
signed between the government and rebels of the Revolutionary
United Front in July. 
</P>
</TEXT>
