<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Suspends Military Sales to Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Britain is suspending all
military sales to Indonesia, Foreign Secretary Robin Cook said on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"The British government will take national action to suspend
existing contracts, including the Hawk contract," Cook told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
Cook made the remarks just hours after defense ministry
officials said that the delivery of nine more Hawk jets to
Indonesia would go ahead despite the East Timor crisis.
</P>
<P>
"We are not embarrassed by this and we are in fact pleased that
we are now taking this action to make sure we bring home to the
Indonesian government and particularly its army the horror and the
disgust of the international community at what's being done in
East Timor," he told reporters.
</P>
<P>
He said that Britain would heed East Timor's "cry for freedom"
and was ready to take part if Indonesia agreed to let an
international peacekeeping force into that territory.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister added that Britain would "support an
European Union arms embargo" against Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
The suspension of the delivery of the nine ground-attack Hawk
jets, under a 1980s deal signed by the Conservative government,
was regarded as a sudden U-turn of the Labor government.
</P>
<P>
Britain's arms sale to Jakarta was widely criticized recently
after hundreds of civilian Timorese were reported killed.
</P>
<P>
Jakarta is currently under considerable international pressure
to halt the massacres in East Timor carried out by
anti-independence militias angered by the territory's overwhelming
vote on August 30 in favor of ending Indonesian rule.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
