<HEADLINE> D'Alema Urges More Courageous Push to Italian Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Italian Premier Massimo D'Alema
Saturday opened the 63rd Trade and Industrial Fair of the southern
Adriatic port of Bari with an appeal to Italian entrepreneurs to
take a more courageous approach to business innovation.
</P>
<P>
According to Italian news agency Ansa, D'Alema told Italian
businessmen that the government was doing its part to boost Italian
economic growth but asked them to "give a more courageous push in the
direction of innovation in terms of products and services offered."
</P>
<P>
"Italy is starting along the right road in terms of development and
innovation, our aim is seeing through to its conclusion the challenge
of modernization," D'Alema continued.
</P>
<P>
Turning to employment issues, the premier said that the latest data
from the national statistics bureau Istat showed that 523,000 new jobs
had been created over the last three years.
</P>
<P>
He said that these jobs were termed "precarious" in the sense that
they did not involve a permanent contract, but he said that it was
wrong to view the employment issue in terms of permanent jobs only.
</P>
<P>
He said that greater job flexibility was a bonus and that the new
jobs were largely the result of measures introduced to increase this
flexibility.
</P>
<P>
D'Alema said that the underdeveloped southern half of Italy
required more infrastructure and services and that "a modern,
efficient state has the duty to remedy this."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
