<BODY>
<HEADLINE> LeBlanc Pleased With Choice of New Canadian Governor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Out-going Canadian Governor
General Romeo LeBlanc is pleased with the choice of Madame
Adrienne Clarkson as his successor.
</P>
<P>
"I think she's somebody that's pretty busy," LeBlanc said
Saturday, referring to the "energy she showed" at meetings with
universities and on other occasions.
</P>
<P>
"She will bring a whole new approach to it, which is what each
Governor General does," he made such comments after attending a
ceremony in memory of a historic war in Welland, Ontario.
</P>
<P>
Being Governor General of Canada is a hectic job in the highest
public office. During his term from 1995, LeBlanc has attended 1,
852 events and invited 68,677 guests to the Rideau Hall.
</P>
<P>
Local press said Clarkson's energy would no doubt help her cope
with what LeBlanc called a busy job.
</P>
<P>
Clarkson will take office on October 7, 1999 as Canada's 26th
Governor General, the second woman governor and the first one of
Chinese descent.
</P>
<P>
Clarkon, now 60, was born in Hong Kong in 1939. She came to
Canada as a refugee with her family during World War II in 1942.
She had served as Chairwoman of the Board of Trustees of the
Canadian Museum of Civilization in Hull, Quebec, until Wednesday's
announcement of her appointment by Prime Minister Jean Chretien.
</P>
</TEXT>
