<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian Scientist Challenges Big Bang With New Theory </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 12 (Xinhua) -- A leading Indian astronomer
challenged Big Bang, the most accepted theory of universe
formation so far, with a new concept called Quasi Steady Cosmology
(QSSC).
</P>
<P>
Being developed by Jayant V. Narlikar, director of Inter
University Center for Astronomy and Astrophysics (IUCAA) based in
Pune, 1,400 kilometers south of here, along with British
Astronomer Fred Hoyle and two other IUCAA scientists, the theory
revolves around the idea of several mini-creation events instead
of one Big Bang.
</P>
<P>
Narlikar told the press here on Sunday that his new concept
could provide answers to some intriguing cosmological questions
whose answers based on the Big Bang theory were not satisfactory.
</P>
<P>
Though the idea was first proposed by Narlikar and Hoyle about
three decades ago, they are now using the theory to understand the
pattern of formation and growth of large structures like galaxies
and voids with modern computer simulation techniques.
</P>
<P>
According to the Big Bang theory, the universe was evolved from
a huge explosion. Unlike common explosions that start from a
definite center and spread out engulfing the surroundings, Big
Bang occurred simultaneously everywhere and before Big Bang, there
was no matter, energy and even time.
</P>
<P>
Though some experimental evidences did exist in support of the
theory, Narlikar said, it is yet to be accepted universally as it
fails to satisfactorily answer a fundamental question -- what
preceded Big Bang?
</P>
<P>
In contrast, the Indian astronomer said, matter was not created
from a single epoch-making event like Big Bang but evolved
continuously from an energy reservoir called "creation field."
</P>
<P>
According to his concept of QSSC, there was no beginning of the
universe as proposed by the Big Bang theory.
</P>
<P>
QSSC provides an alternative to explain cosmological features
described by the Big Bang theory including the formation of large
structures like galaxies and voids in a different way.
</P>
<P>
The model was tested by computer simulation and preliminary
results were "remarkable," Narlikar said, adding that, however, it
needs more fine-tuning.
</P>
<P>
Matter is created in the universe out of the creation field by
mini-bangs or mini-creation events, according to the QSSC theory,
but the rate of matter formation varies with time as the
mini-creations are not switched on continually.
</P>
<P>
Mini-bangs occur in the vicinity of compact massive objects,
each producing a local expansion of space which contributes to the
overall expansion of the universe.
</P>
<P>
At the same time there are phases where mini-creation events
are switched off and at this stage, expansion slows down only to
be accelerated after certain time.
</P>
<P>
The up-and-down creation activity helps maintain the overall
expansion of the universe, according to the new theory. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
