<HEADLINE> Britain Urges Fast Assembling of Peacekeepers into E.Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Britain on Sunday welcomed the
decision by Indonesian President B.J. Habibie to invite U.N.
peacekeepers into East Timor and urged the peacekeeping force to
be assembled quickly.
</P>
<P>
"We will now be looking for details of their commitment and for
their commitment to a U.N. peacekeeping force to be carried out
rapidly and in full," Robin Cook, Britain's Foreign Secretary,
told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Cook said 250 British Army Nepalese Gurkhas, pledged by Britain
to the U.N. peacekeeping force, would be among the first
peacekeepers to arrive in East Timor, probably within days.
</P>
<P>
He said Sir Jeremy Greenstock, Britain's ambassador to the
United Nations, had spoken to Habibie, who promised that work
should start immediately at the U.N. headquarters in New York to
prepare the international force for East Timor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
