<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Death Toll From Athens Earthquake Rises to 115 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, September 12 (Xinhua) -- The death toll from Tuesday's
earthquake in northwestern Athens rose to 115 Sunday as
aftershocks continued to hit the region.
</P>
<P>
Greece's Health Ministry said that it had so far registered 115
dead from Tuesday's earthquake registering 5.9 on the Richter
scale.
</P>
<P>
An aftershock measuring 4.2 on the Richter scale rocked Athens
at 9:17 a.m. Sunday, and seismologists said that the tremor was a
logical extension of Tuesday's powerful earthquake, which had an
epicenter in Mount Parnitha, some 20 kilometers northwest of
Athens.
</P>
<P>
It was rumored that a strong earthquake would hit Athens soon,
but the Athens Observatory described this as "groundless rumors,"
saying that aftershocks were being registered at wide intervals
and aftershock activity was developing normally.
</P>
<P>
The observatory said that aftershocks were expected to continue
for some weeks.
</P>
<P>
The state engineers have so far made 37,155 inspections. Fifty
percent of homes have been found suitable for habitation, 39
percent in need of repair, and 11 percent in need of demolition.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, Greece has decided to establish a
commission made up of leading scientists and academics to examine
the reasons of why so many buildings collapsed in Tuesday's
earthquake, which is estimated to cost the country 100 billion
drachmas (about 333 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The commission will present a report to the Ministry of
Environment, Town Planning and Public Works by the end of this
month.
</P>
<P>
The Greek government has determined to bring those responsible
for the collapsed buildings to justice. 
</P>
</TEXT>
