<DOCNO> XIE19990912.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> African Countries Urged to Fight Against AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Africans have been urged to
spare no effort in deploying resources for the fight against AIDS
at the dawn of the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
Officially opening the 11th International Conference on AIDS
and STDS (sexually transmitted diseases) in Africa (ICASA) here on
Sunday, Zambian Vice-President Christon Tembo said, "we must bring
our accumulated experiences, expertise and resources to bear on
the challenge of responding more meaningfully and purposefully to
the HIV/AIDS pandemic, which now threatens the very existence of
humanity".
</P>
<P>
According to estimates, he said, HIV infections are highest on
the African continent. Many African countries, particularly those
of sub- Saharan Africa, are facing increasing, or at best steady
rates of HIV transmission.
</P>
<P>
For example, in most capital cities of the southern African
countries, it is not uncommon to find HIV infection levels in
excess of 20 percent of the adult population, he added.
</P>
<P>
He said that the loss of youngsters in the prime of their lives
 is particularly devastating on Africa's economic development and
productivity in African countries.
</P>
<P>
"At the dawn of the new millennium, Africa must emerge on the
global arena with not only resolve to rise above conflicts and
civil war, but also start to build upon and strengthen practical
approaches to prevent the further spread of HIV/AIDS and to
mitigate its impact," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Themed "Looking into the future: Setting priorities for
HIV/AIDS/STDs in Africa", the week-long international conference
will examine the social and economic impact of HIV/AIDS in Africa
.
</P>
<P>
About 6,000 participants from 63 countries attended the
conference together with representatives from the United Nations,
the World Health Organization and some regional organizations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
