<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-12 14:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Ministers Meeting Discusses Key Arab </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Iraq took over chairmanship of
the Arab League's biannual foreign ministers' meeting here Sunday,
stressing Arab unity against outside threats.
</P>
<P>
The meeting opened with delegates from 21 Arab states and
the Palestinian National Authority standing for a moment of
silence for King Hassan II of Morocco, who died in August.
</P>
<P>
During the two-day meeting, Arab foreign ministers and foreign
ministry officials are expected to discuss the United Nations
sanctions on Iraq and Libya and a call for an Arab summit to reach
a united position on peace talks between Arab countries and Israel.
</P>
<P>
The outgoing chairman, Somali ambassador to the league Abdullah
Mahmoud, welcomed the election of Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak as a step toward peace.
</P>
<P>
Mahmoud also referred to the United States-British airstrikes
against Iraq as an example of hostility against the Arab
world. Not condemning the attacks, he said they target civilians
more than the Iraqi military.
</P>
<P>
For the first time since it invaded Kuwait in 1990, Iraq took
over the chair according to the league's rotation of the seat
among member countries.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Foreign Minister Mohammed Saeed al-Sahhaf said the
league's priority was Arab unity. He said he favored an Arab
summit, or a meeting at a lower level, as a response to the U.S
imposition of hegemony on the region.
</P>
<P>
In his opening speech, Arab League Secretary-General Esmat
Abdel-Meguid called on the U.N. Security Council to lift sanctions
on Libya over the 1988 Lockerbie bombing, since Tripoli had handed
over the two Libyans suspected of blowing up a Pan Am airliner in
Lockerbie, Scotland.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat, who received a standing
ovation on entering the meeting, emphasized that the 3 million
Palestinian refugees have the right to return to the
territories. He dismissed reports that the large number of
Palestinians in Lebanon might become permanent residents.
</P>
<P>
Arafat said he hoped the revised Wye accord signed on September
5 would be a new beginning for peace negotiations between Syria,
Lebanon, the Palestinians and Israel. He also stressed the
importance of East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
"There can be no peace without Jerusalem, free (of Israeli
occupation) and as the capital of a Palestinian state," he said.
</P>
<P>
Among the other 46 points on the agenda are a proposal for a
united Arab airline and a call by the Palestinians and the United
Arab Emirates (UAE) to ban Arab participation in an upcoming
Israeli exhibit at Disney's Epcot Center in Florida, U.S..
</P>
<P>
The exhibit reportedly depicts Jerusalem as the capital of
Israel. The UAE has said it will boycott all Disney products if
the exhibit opens. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990912.0054 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Defense Communications Network </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 12 (Xinhua) -- China has established a sound
nationwide integrated communications network for national defense
purposes, according to a meeting on combat readiness in the
communications sector held here today.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, the country railways, communications,
information industry and civil aviation departments have joined
the efforts to combine national defense with economic development,
participants were told.
</P>
<P>
The military has spent heavily on improving special railways to
make them ready, and related military facilities have been
upgraded.
</P>
<P>
There are 96 highways that can be used for national defense
purposes and 4,000 kilometers of military highways that have been
re-built.
</P>
<P>
The country has done work on 45 airports, with military needs
taken into consideration in the process.
</P>
<P>
Efforts have also been made to explore ways to mobilize ships
at sea for military purpose.  
</P>
</TEXT>
