<HEADLINE> UN Lashes Taliban for Poor Women Rights Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 12 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Special Rapporteur for
Violence Against women Radhika Coomaraswami Sunday criticized
Afghanistan's ruling Taliban for "systematic violations" of the
human rights of women.
</P>
<P>
"We found widespread violations of the human rights of women in
the Taliban areas of Afghanistan," Coomaraswami told a news
conference here on return from a four-day visit to Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
She said she and her team found violations of women's physical
security, the right to education, health, employment and movement
freedom.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban's Ministry of Vice and Virtue has authored edicts
that ban women from working and going to school, force them to
wear the all-encompassing burqua and order people to paint their
first-floor windows black so passers-by could not see women
inside.
</P>
<P>
Afghan women are also prohibited from traveling outside their
home without the company of a close male relative. Violators are
publicly beaten, Coomaraswami said.
</P>
<P>
She said discrimination against women exists throughout the
world but in Afghanistan it is the official policy of the Taliban.
</P>
<P>
The ruling militia has imposed its own interpretation of
Islamic law in the areas which account for more than 80 percent of
the war-ravaged country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
