<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Accepts Peacekeeping Force to E. Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President B.J.
Habibie announced here Sunday that his government accepted a
U.N.-sponsored international peacekeeping force in cooperation
with the country's military to restore order and security in East
Timor.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in a televised speech at the presidential palace
Sunday evening, the president stressed the importance of bringing
peace to the violence-torn territory.
</P>
<P>
He admitted that since the imposition of martial law in East
Timor, the Indonesian military was reported to be still facing
some limits, which he said are much attributable to psychological
difficulties, thus hampering the security forces to take steps
toward creating stability in the territory.
</P>
<P>
It was said Indonesian Foreign Minister Ali Alatas will go to
New York Sunday night to discuss the arrangement for the sending
of a U.N. peacekeeping force to East Timor.
</P>
<P>
The discussion will be on which countries will join the
peacekeeping force and who will finance the U.N. actions in East
Timor.
</P>
<P>
Violence has taken place since the announcement of the August
30 ballot result in East Timor by the United Nations on September
4, which showed that over 78 percent of the East Timorese voters
cast their votes for independence.
</P>
<P>
Although the Indonesian military declared a status of emergency
in East Timor on September 7, the violence has not been stopped
completely. Reports said more than 100 people have been killed and
tens of thousands of houses have been burned down during the
violence.
</P>
<P>
In the face of the situation, the United Nations and some
western countries have called on the Indonesian government to
invite international forces to East Timor for the restoration of
security and order in the territory.
</P>
<P>
Under an agreement signed with the United Nations in May,
Indonesia is responsible for security and order in East Timor
before and after the ballot.
</P>
<P>
East Timor, a former Portuguese colony, was integrated into
Indonesia in 1976, but the move has never been recognized by the
United Nations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
