<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Export-Oriented Economy Helping China's Growth (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIAMEN, September 12 (Xinhua) -- The new government foreign
investment policies China made known over the weekend show that
the country has made its most significant economic readjustment in
recent years to help sustain economic development.
</P>
<P>
At the Third China Investment and Trade Fair in Xiamen, Fujian
Province, which ended today, China announced that the country
plans to open its service trade to overseas investors and
encourage them to engage in technical development, invest in the
central and western parts of China, and improve the management and
services of foreign-funded enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Ma Xiuhong, assistant minister of foreign trade and economic
cooperation, said that the goal of the new policies is to adjust
the country's industrial structure and promote coordinated
development in different regions.
</P>
<P>
Since China opened to the outside world two decades ago,
economic growth has been affected by developments in other
countries, according to a State Development Planning Commission
report.
</P>
<P>
It said the Asian financial crisis and the global retrenchment
of 1997 had a strong impact on China's economy and caused great
difficulties in its macro-economic operations, resulting in a drop
in both the number of new foreign-funded enterprises and the
amount of contracted and paid-in foreign investment from January
to July this year.
</P>
<P>
Chinese analysts say that it is not enough to stop the economic
retrenchment by expanding domestic demand and that a changed
export-oriented strategy is the real answer.
</P>
<P>
At the just-concluded investment and trade fair, senior Chinese
officials said that China should choose outside resources suitable
for its development and change the policy from "imbalanced
development" to "balanced development".
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990912.0068 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Export-Oriented Economy Helping China's Growth (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
China has announced that more areas will be chosen for
experiment to attract foreign investment in the fields of finance,
insurance, foreign trade, commerce and telecommunications, as well
as accounting, assessing and legal services.
</P>
<P>
This is seen by many as a breakthrough China has made in
opening to the outside world.
</P>
<P>
Hu Angang, of the Chinese Academy of Sciences, said that
foreign-funded enterprises have provided 18 million jobs for the
Chinese, mostly in manufacturing, and if China opens the service
trade market to other countries, more jobs will be created.
</P>
<P>
State Councilor Wu Yi expressed the hope that foreigners will
invest more in central and western parts of China, just as they
did in the coastal areas a decade or more ago.
</P>
<P>
Central and western parts of China have 60 percent of the
population but only 12 percent of the foreign investment that has
flowed into the country so far. It is obvious that only by
encouraging investment in these areas, can China's goal of
developing in an all-round way be reached.
</P>
<P>
Promoting industrial improvements will be central task for
future economic growth, Wu said. At the fair many regions offered
overseas investors with opportunities in the fields of mobile
communication, automobile manufacturing, building materials,
electricity production and sensitive materials.
</P>
<P>
Wu Yi said that China is trying to become an assembly,
manufacturing and sales center for multinationals, and what is
more important is to make the country a technological development
center for these business giants.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
