<DOCNO> XIE19990912.0069 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Money Supply Picking Up in August </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 12 (Xinhua) -- China's central bank, the
People's Bank of China (PBOC), reported today that the financial
sector had steady growth in August, with the money supply rising
after July's slowdown.
</P>
<P>
At the end of August, the outstanding broad money (currency in
circulation plus corporate deposits and savings deposits) stood at
11.28 trillion, up 16 percent from the same period last year, and
0.3 percentage points from July this year, while narrow money (
cash plus demand deposits) stood at 4.01 trillion yuan, up 14.4
percent from August last year and 0.9 percentage points from July
this year.
</P>
<P>
And cash in circulation picked up 12.5 percent to 1.13 trillion
yuan from August last year and up 0.9 percentage points from July
this year.
</P>
<P>
Outstanding loans of financial institutions amounted to 9.21
trillion yuan, up 13.9 percent from August last year and 0.1
percentage points from July this year. Loans grew in the first
eight months by 571.3 billion yuan, 47.6 billion yuan of that
going to the industrial sector, 45.6 billion yuan to agriculture,
and 120.2 billion yuan to infrastructure construction.
</P>
<P>
By the end of August, financial institutions had deposits of 10.
37 trillion yuan, up 16.3 percent from August last year, with
enterprises accounting for 3.39 trillion yuan of that, up 0.6
percentage points from July this year. Enterprise deposits in
August increased 87.5 billion yuan, an increase of 26.5 billion
yuan more than that for the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Individual deposits amounted to 5.91 trillion yuan, up 16.3
percent, but 0.3 percentage points less than for July this year.
</P>
<P>
By the end of August, the renminbi exchange rate was 8.2770
yuan to one U.S. dollar, up 17 basic points from the same time
last year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
