<HEADLINE> China to Take New Measures to Encourage Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIAMEN, September 12 (Xinhua) -- China is to take more measures
to encourage exports, according to Wen Zaixing, a spokesman for
the Third China Investment and Trade Fair which ended here today.
</P>
<P>
China's exports this year are still stuck with negative growth
so the Chinese government will adopt a series of new measures,
like reducing the amount of red tape and fees, Wen told
participants here today.
</P>
<P>
In recent months, the government has unveiled measures aimed at
promoting foreign trade and economic cooperation. On July 1, China
raised its overall rebate rate for exports by 2.95 percentage
points to about 15 percent and is considering more favorable tax
breaks for high-tech exports.
</P>
<P>
On the financial front, the People's Bank of China, the central
bank, and the Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation
published a notice on closed-end loans to foreign trade businesses
and China shortened its list of export quotas and decreased the
number of restrictions on businesses that want to get involved in
foreign trade and economic cooperation. 
</P>
