<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Western China Appeals to Overseas Investors (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIAMEN, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Signs at the 3rd China
Investment and Trade Fair suggest that China's policy of shifting
its economic emphasis to the central and western parts of the
country has made great impact on overseas investors.
</P>
<P>
In the first three days of the China Investment and Trade Fair
which closed today in Xiamen in southeast China's coastal province
of Fujian, 19 provinces and cities in the central and western
parts of China have concluded 252 contracts involving a total
investment of 1.25 billion U.S. dollars, 32 percent of the fair's
total trade volume.
</P>
<P>
Some 780 million U.S. dollars, or 26 percent of the contracted
funds, will come from abroad, said an official of the organizing
committee.
</P>
<P>
Compared with provinces in China's eastern part, the central
and western parts have been slow in economic growth as a result of
unfavorable geographical conditions, lack of funds and other
factors.
</P>
<P>
By 1997, The number of overseas-funded enterprises and the
amount of investment which had been used in the central and
western parts of China made up only 17.2 and 12.5 percent of the
country's total respectively.
</P>
<P>
Facts show that there exists a serious imbalance in regional
economic growth with the emphasis laying too much on coastal areas
in the eastern part.
</P>
<P>
In recent year, China has gradually shifted its center of
economic development to the central and western parts to
accelerate development of the resources-rich regions, attain
common prosperity and ensure China's sustainable economic growth
as a whole.
</P>
<P>
An official with the Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic
Cooperation (MOFTEC) announced at the Second China Investment and
Trade Fair held last year that the central government would grant
the central and western parts a more preferential policy on the
use of overseas funds to encourage more overseas investors to come
to the region.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
