<DOCNO> XIE19990912.0084 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Oldest Ethnic Group Increasing Contact With Outside World </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, September 12 (Xinhua) -- The Qiang, one of China's
oldest ethnic groups, are working hard building roads to increase
contacts with the modern world.
</P>
<P>
Historical records say that the Qiang were one of the most
powerful ethnic groups in China and had many dynasties that ruled
a large number of people and vast lands. But over the centuries,
they were pushed back farther and farther into mountainous parts
of in southern China.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, their numbers had shrunk to fewer than 40,000 by
1949, when the People's Republic was founded. But the figure
became 200,000 in the past five decades thanks to the government's
ethnic minority policies.
</P>
<P>
The Qiang learned from history that they would lose all
opportunity for development if they did not make the outside world
more accessible, and building roads was the only way.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, they have spent every cent on roads, according
to Xie Shixu, a government official in Maoxian County, southwest
China's Sichuan Province, where half of the 200,000 Qiang people
live.
</P>
<P>
One of the people who played a key role was Yang Songying, a
Qiang woman who is a deputy to the National People's Congress. She
and other villagers from Tongxinba village worked for three years
on a 3.5 km road and made the village a model of road building.
</P>
<P>
Neighboring villages have followed their example and a road
network has formed in the mountainous county. Visitors marvel at
the quality of the mountain roads in the area, but what may really
surprise them is the cost: about a tenth that of roads built in
developed areas of the country.
</P>
<P>
While both the central and local government financed the road
projects, the locals in Maoxian county also contributed in both
financial resources and free labor service. Meng Fei, a Qiang poet,
says that the impoverished Qiang built roads with their blood. He'
s referring to the six construction workers who died in a work-
related accident.
</P>
<P>
The roads have linked the Qiang with the outside world and
increased the flow of materials, cash, and people, which has led
to the growth of industries, including tourism.
</P>
<P>
The Qiang used to look down on business people and were
reluctant to contact outsiders, but this way of thinking has
changed, and shops, restaurants, and hotels have appeared, with
visitors from other parts of the country and abroad coming in.
</P>
<P>
Yan Yiqing, the owner of a summer resort and the richest
private businessman in Maoxian, says that his forefathers lived in
isolation and were shy about dealing with strangers. But, young
people now travel on business and talk with clients over the phone
or via fax or the Internet. What a change, he says.  
