<HEADLINE> Hosts Halves Judo Titles in Chinese City Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YAN'AN, SHAANXI, China, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Hosts Xi'an
halved the first four judo titles at stake while Hong Kong Tai
Kwong Yee was eliminated in the opening round of the fourth
Chinese City Games here on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Fuyan took the men's 66-kg category judo title while his
women teammate Zhao Shunxin triumphed in the 48-kg class, as
applauses echoed in the full-packed Yan'an Sports Stadium.
</P>
<P>
Tai Kwong Yee, a 19-year-old Hong Kong player, failed to
advance further as he was stopped in the opener although his coach
Li Hung had hoped him to reap the men's 66-kg title as he was the
only Hong Kong male player present at the Games.
</P>
<P>
"I was really nervous in the competitions, but I also had to
acknowledge the fact that many a judo players here are of high
quality," said the Hong Kong player, a company salesman.
</P>
<P>
"His teammate Cheng Wai Yee, the only woman judoka from Hong
Kong, had recorded the game from the stands, and we will study the
video tape once we back to Hong Kong," said coach Li.
</P>
<P>
Yan'an, the holy land of China, was one of the four co-costs
for the City Games, which was being held for the first time in
China's northwestern region.
</P>
<P>
"A lot of changes have impressed me deeply and Yan'an leaves me
a great impression that people here are becoming open-minded more
and more," said the 43-year-old Hong Kong coach.
</P>
<P>
To host the City Games, Shaanxi provincial government has
invested nearly one billion yuans (some 102 million US dollars)
for 11 new sports facilities. 
</P>
