<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-12 11:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arab FM Meeting Opens Under Iraq's Chairmanship </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Arab foreign ministers kicked
off their bi-annual meeting in Cairo on Sunday with Iraq in the
chair for the first time since its 1990 invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Foreign ministers and foreign ministry officials from 21 Arab
states and the Palestinian National Authority (PNA) are expected
to discuss the U.N. sanctions on Iraq and a call for an Arab
summit to reach a united position on peace talks between Arab
countries and Israel.
</P>
<P>
PNA President Yasser Arafat will likely brief participants on
the revised Wye accord signed September 5, under which the
Palestinians and Israel planned to draw up a framework for final
peace talks by February 15 and complete the process by September
2000.
</P>
<P>
Among the other 46 points on the agenda are a proposal for a
united Arab airline and a call by the PNA and the United Arab
Emirates (UAE) to ban Arab participation in an upcoming Israeli
exhibit at Disney's Epcot Center in Florida, the United States.
</P>
<P>
The exhibit reportedly depicts Jerusalem as the capital of
Israel. The UAE has already announced it will boycott all Disney
products if the exhibit opens.
</P>
<P>
Regardless of the agenda issues, all eyes are on Iraqi Foreign
Minister Mohammad Said al-Sahaf, who took the chair on an
alphabetical rotation basis among member states. At the last Arab
foreign ministers' meeting in January, al-Sahaf stormed out in a
fury over his colleagues' failure to condemn U.N. sanctions and
the U.S.-British airstrikes on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Arab League Secretary General Esmat Abdel-Meguid has urged
al-Sahaf to use the chair to pursue reconciliation. On several
occasions after he arrived here on Friday, al-Sahaf said Iraq
supports all initiatives aimed at restoring Arab unity, which was
jeopardized by Iraq's 1990 invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Iraq's invasion of Kuwait prompted U.N. economic sanctions,
which will not be lifted until it is verified that Iraq has
eliminated its weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and Britain launched four-day airstrikes in December
against Iraq in retaliation for what the Western allies denounced
as Baghdad's failure to comply with the U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday after meeting with Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa, al-Sahaf said Iraq has fully complied with the U.N.
resolutions and demanded lifting of the economic sanctions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
