<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 12 (Xinhua) -- The following are brief economic
news from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The Egyptian Ministry of Industry is considering
measures to raise the minimum percentage of locally manufactured
car parts from 40 percent to 60 percent in three years, the
Arabic-language Al Hayat daily reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
However, such measures will not cover air-conditioning and
radio-cassette sets which are considered as luxury items.
</P>
<P>
Local car companies have been negotiating with their
counterparts of other countries which supply component parts to
joint ventures engaged in the production of spare parts for export
purposes and for ensuring the needs of local car factories.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Egypt witnessed a rise in imports of car component
parts to approximately 600 million U.S. dollars. There are 13 car
factories in Egypt which produce about 50,000 cars a year.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The amount of cargo transiting through the Suez Canal
during the first seven months of 1999 has slightly declined to
223.8 million tons, down by 400,000 tons from 224.2 million tons
as compared to the corresponding period of last year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the number of ships transiting the Canal during the
same period stood at 7,740, down by 216 ships from 7,956 during the
corresponding period of last year, the Arabic-language Al Hayat
newspaper reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
RAMALLA -- The World Bank has extended 380 million U.S. dollars in
grants and soft loans to the Palestinian National Authority ever
since 1993, said a bank official.
</P>
<P>
RIYADH -- All Saudi banks are due to conduct emergency tests on
their computer sets before the end of September to check the Y2K
problem.
</P>
<P>
Local Iqtissadiya newspaper quoted Ibrahim Al Harabi, leader of
the adaptation team for the year 2000 problem at the Saudi
Monetary Fund/Central Bank Foundation, as saying that the tests
will evaluate human reaction in case of a flop in the sets or a
failure in electricity, should the unamended programs fail to read
the new date and hold to 1900's. 
</P>
</TEXT>
