<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Make All Chinese As Fit As Fiddle (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 12 (Xinhua) -- "I have a dream, that one day
all Chinese are as fit as fiddle," said Ma hua, a popular aerobics
teacher in China.
</P>
<P>
Having taught aerobics in a sports program of China Central TV
for many years, Ma is well-known among Chinese citizens, and her
name is often related to figure building or shaping.
</P>
<P>
Looking at Ma, who is well in perfect shape, one cannot imagine
she was such a skinny girl before she took to shaping some 15
years ago.
</P>
<P>
"In those days I was so thin and tall, as good as a bamboo,"
she recalled with a smile, proud of her present stature.
</P>
<P>
Sitting in an armchair in the cafe of her fitness club, Ma told
Xinhua that she never thought she would become an aerobics teacher
until she took a fancy in disco in the early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
"Disco was so fascinating to youngsters at that time just like
the internet to young people in the mid-1990s. I turned to some
choreographers to learn disco who regarded my dancing as something
more like aerobics rather than disco, and that changed my life."
</P>
<P>
Ma took up aerobics teaching in 1985, at a time when disco, let
alone aerobics, was unfamiliar to most Chinese citizens.
</P>
<P>
"Believe it or not, I taught my first class in a shabby
classroom in the then Institute of Physical Education in Beijing,
and dancing with me are a group of faddy girls." Ma told the story
in retrospect.
</P>
<P>
In contrast, the well-equipped Mahua Fitness Club, which opened
in November last year, covers an area of 900 square meters and
receives more than 300 visitors each day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
