<DOCNO> XIE19990912.0101 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Make All Chinese As Fit As Fiddle (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
And, improvements in the standard of living have caused people
to understand this more. Many middle-aged urbanites, who were used
a frugal life in the past, are more willing to pay a quarter of
their average monthly income for exercise classes three times a
week.
</P>
<P>
A large number of her students are above 40 and most suffer
from occupational diseases and doing so is just a wise move, she
explained. Some common but dangerous illnesses like hypertension
and coronary heart disease can be prevented through exercise. And
a little exercise a day can keep the doctor away, she added,
recommending that people take her as an example.
</P>
<P>
Fitness clubs have a promising future and can be found in many
Chinese cities. There are several dozen in Beijing with all sorts
of facilities and services, but they couldn't possibly meet the
demand of the potential market of a city of this size.
</P>
<P>
Ma Hua has four branches in other cities and four more planned.
In the future, she'll cover all of China and give everybody access
to the benefits of a healthy body, she said.  
</P>
