<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senior Chinese, U.S. Officials Discuss Relations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AUCKLAND, New Zealand, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-
Premier Qian Qichen met with U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright and Assistant to the President for National Security
Affairs Samuel Berger here Sunday to discuss China-U.S. relations
and other major issues of common concern.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, Qian said that the China-U.S. relations have
witnessed ups and downs and difficulties in recent years, and that
some experience and lessons should be drawn on in this respect.
</P>
<P>
Both sides should promote the development of relations between
the two countries, Qian noted.
</P>
<P>
On the international situation, Qian said that currently there
are many international problems, including regional conflicts.
Such problems should still be settled in accordance with norms
governing international relations, such as the mutual respect of
sovereignty and territorial integrity, non-interference in others'
internal affairs and peaceful settlement of disputes.
</P>
<P>
The norms are not outdated, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Albright said the United States also considers the world as a
multi-polar one, is willing to cooperate with China, Russia and
the European Union, and attaches importance to the role of the
United Nations.
</P>
<P>
On the issue of Taiwan, Qian said that China and the United
States have exchanged views many times in recent years, and
reaffirmed that China's basic policies on settlement of the Taiwan
issue are "peaceful reunification" and "one country, two systems."
</P>
<P>
China will continue to make efforts toward that end, he noted.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that the United States will prudently and
appropriately handle the Taiwan issue.
</P>
<P>
Albright said that the summit meeting between Chinese President
Jiang Zemin and his U.S. counterpart Bill Clinton here on Saturday
was very significant, and that the United States values its
extensive relations with China.
</P>
<P>
Such relations are important to both the United States and
China, she said.
</P>
<P>
Berger said the United States views the U.S.-China summit on
Saturday as turning over a new leaf in the bilateral relations,
and that both sides should continue to make efforts and cooperate
with each other to expand common interests.
</P>
<P>
The senior Chinese and U.S. officials are here in company of
their respective top leaders to attend the two-day seventh
informal meeting of leaders of the Asia-Pacific Economic
Cooperation (APEC) forum, which opened here Sunday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
