<HEADLINE> Ebola Kills Seven in Congo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, September 12 (Xinhua) -- A new Ebola-like fever has
killed seven people in the gold mines in the Democratic Republic
of the Congo (DRC) , including a Ugandan soldier, the New Vision
paper reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
World Health Organization (WHO) officials reported that so far
73 people have died of the haemorrhagic fever caused by the virus
leading to rapid fatal internal bleeding.
</P>
<P>
There are dead rats, bats and human bodies decomposing in the
gold mines in Durba in the northwestern area of DRC, about 200 km
from Uganda border, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The international health body has called for the closure of
the gold mines. The latest seven victims, including three illegal
gold diggers and one Ugandan serviceman, a WHO official was quoted
as saying.
</P>
<P>
Although the DRC government has decided to close the mines,
the ongoing war has made it impossible to implement the closure,
sending more illegal suicidal miners to their deaths, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
The area is said to be controlled by the rebels and therefore
it is unclear who would have the authority to close down the mines
and save the lives of the miners.
</P>
<P>
Another report said that a plane belonging to the French
medical charity Medicine sans Frontiers flew to Durba on Friday to
collect blood samples taken from the latest victims.  
</P>
</TEXT>
