<HEADLINE> Famous Oilfield Well Developed in Northwest China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XINING, September 12 (Xinhua) -- The Qinghai Oilfield, located
in the Qaidam Basin in the northern part of Qinghai-Tibet Plateau,
produced a total of 15.5 million tons of oil since it was first
built 44 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Its output rose on a year-on-year basis after its annual oil
output surpassed one million tons in 1991. The oilfield's
petroleum and gas output in 1998 topped the 2 million-ton mark.
The daily crude oil output has risen from 3,000 tons in 1994 to
present 54,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
The Qaidam Basin, with a total area of 250,000 sq km, is
regarded as the treasure basin of the country. It has an oil
reserve of 4.1 billion tons and proven gas reserve of 150 billion
cubic meters, making it the fourth largest gasfield in China after
Sichuan Province, Shaanxi-Gansu-Ningxia Region, and Tarim Basin in
the Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
Scientists succeeded in digging an exploring shaft in Lenghu
block in northwestern part of Qaidam Basin last year. The related
study of the Lengke NO.1 oil well proved that the Jurassic system
oil-bearing rocks coverage there was 13,000 sq km with a thickness
of 1,300 m.
</P>
<P>
Oil experts believe that Qaidam Basin will be China's leading
energy reserve base in the 21st century. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
