<DOCNO> XIE19990912.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia, Indonesia, Thailand to Discuss Cooperation on Rubber </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia, Thailand and
Indonesia, the three world major natural rubber producers, will
discuss cooperation in rubber production and other related
matters, Malaysian Primary Industries Minister Lim Keng Yaik said
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The three largest natural rubber producers in the world need to
cooperate and establish short- and long-term programs to assist
smallholders in the three countries, he said in the southern state
of Johor, according to Bernama news agency.
</P>
<P>
"If Malaysia, Thailand and Indonesia have an understanding on
production and other related matters concerning the commodity,
then a fall in prices in future could be avoided," he was quoted
as saying.
</P>
<P>
The three countries, which together account for more than 85
percent of world natural rubber production, need to be united in
addressing issues including the possibility of withdrawing from
the International Natural Rubber Organization.
</P>
<P>
A Malaysia-Thailand ministerial meeting would be held in
Pattaya, Thailand from September 16 to 18 while his visit to
Indonesia has yet to be determined, he said, adding that Malaysia
is expected to sign a memorandum of understanding with the Thai
government on matters concerning the commodity during his visit.
</P>
<P>
Lim said that on the domestic front, several proposals will be
submitted to a cabinet committee on ways of assisting
smallholders, which include setting up a fund which would offer
credit to smallholders to replant rubber trees and to buy modern
equipment to improve production, and merging the small-sized
holdings into bigger ones. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
