<HEADLINE> Vice Premier Calls for Efforts to Reform State-owned Firms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEFEI, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice Premier Wu Bangguo
has called for redoubled efforts to implement the Party's policies
on the reform and development of State-owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Wu, also member of the Political Bureau of the Communist Party
of China (CPC) Central Committee, made the call during a fact-
finding tour to east China's Anhui Province from September 6 to 10.
</P>
<P>
The CPC Central Committee and the State Council attach great
importance to the reform of State-owned enterprises, the vice
premier said.
</P>
<P>
Since the beginning of this year, Jiang Zemin, General
Secretary of the CPC Central Committee, has convened a series of
meetings on the subject in cities of Chengdu, Wuhan, Xi'an,
Qingdao, and Dalian.
</P>
<P>
The upcoming 4th Plenary Session of the 15th CPC Central
Committee is to focus on the subject and make decisions on major
issues concerning the restructuring and development of State-owned
enterprises, Wu disclosed.
</P>
<P>
He said it is imperative to see clearly the present situation
of the State-owned enterprises' reform and development, and
further enhance confidence in managing well the enterprises.
</P>
<P>
State-owned enterprises have come to a key juncture of reform
and development, Wu noted.
</P>
<P>
Efforts must be focused now on the restructuring of State-owned
firms, the establishment of a modern enterprise system, the
solution of urgent problems such as excessive labor and backward
technologies, and the improvement of the social security system,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Many State-owned sectors including petrochemicals, machinery,
electronics, light industry, and textiles are turning losses into
profits as a result of deepened reforms, according to the vice
premier. 
</P>
</TEXT>
