<BODY>
<HEADLINE> APEC Leaders Given Traditional Maori Welcome </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AUCKLAND, NEW ZEALAND, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Leaders of the
21-member Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC) forum received
a traditional welcome from the local Maoris on Sunday before
entering the close-door sessions of their seventh informal meeting.
</P>
<P>
The formal welcome, held at the luxurious Carlton Hotel in
downtown Auckland, was filled with exotic ceremonial color.
</P>
<P>
The welcome, called "powhiri," started with a group of Maori
women in traditional dresses chanting a slogan of "Without the
past, there is no future."
</P>
<P>
A group of Maori warriors then performed "haka," or the dance
before battle, likening the group of APEC leaders to an ocean-
going canoe that has arrived from afar and that has been hauled
ashore.
</P>
<P>
When the leaders, led by the host -- New Zealand Prime Minister
Jenny Shipley, were seated, two prominent Maori elders delivered
their speeches of welcome in a traditional way of chanting, first
in their native language and then in English.
</P>
<P>
The speeches of welcome ended with songs underlining the
messages in the speeches.
</P>
<P>
The singing being over, the APEC leaders were presented a
symbolic gift -- a large piece of nephrite jade widely referred to
in New Zealand as greenstone.
</P>
<P>
The whole ceremony of welcome ended with a nose rubbing between
the hosts and guests, and the APEC leaders were seen entering the
close-door sessions.
</P>
<P>
The two-day informal meeting started here Sunday with three
themes put forward by New Zealand: expanding opportunities for
business around the region, strengthening the functioning of
markets, and expanding support for APEC.
</P>
<P>
APEC was established in 1989 in response to the growing
interdependence among Asia-Pacific economies. Grouping 21 regional
economies under its banner, it was set up to improve the stability,
security and prosperity of its peoples.
</P>
<P>
The economic body comprises Australia, Brunei, Canada, Chile,
China, China's Hong Kong, Indonesia, Japan, Malaysia, Mexico, New
Zealand, Papua New Guinea, Peru, the Philippines, Russia,
Singapore, South Korea, Chinese Taipei, Thailand, the United
States and Vietnam. 
</P>
</TEXT>
