<HEADLINE> New Book Reveals Tight Structure of Falun Gong Cult </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Only two million Chinese
people joined in the Falun Gong cult led by Li Hongzhi, who had
claimed that the number of practitioners was as many as 100
million, according to a new book published here.
</P>
<P>
The book, entitled "Li Hongzhi and His 'Falun Gong'-- Deceiving
the Public and Ruining Lives", also reveals the tight structure of
Falun Gong, which has been banned in the country since last July.
</P>
<P>
The "Research Society of Falun Dafa" was the top national organ
of the Falun Gong organization, and Li was its chairman, the book
says.
</P>
<P>
The society set up 39 general instruction offices, 1,900
ordinary instruction offices, and 28,000 practice sites throughout
the country.
</P>
<P>
Li's directives were relayed by the society to the various
general instruction offices, which then passed them to the
ordinary instruction offices, practice sites and individual
practitioners, it notes.
</P>
<P>
The Falun Gong organization demanded the practitioners should
go to the instruction offices and practice sites to practice every
day. They also held collective activities at regular intervals.
</P>
<P>
In fact, the Falun Gong organization "simply became tools
enabling Li to engage in all sorts of law-breaking activities,"
the book says.
</P>
<P>
After the true features of Li were brought to light, the
overwhelming majority of the practitioners suddenly woke up to
their misjudgment and severed their ties with the illegal
organization, it notes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
