<HEADLINE> Indonesian President to Make Important Statement on E. Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President B.J.
Habibie is expected to make an important statement on East Timor
at around 07:00 p.m. local time (1200 GMT) Sunday, the official
Antara News Agency said.
</P>
<P>
Antara did not say what the president will announce at a press
conference to be held at the presidential palace, but some sources
predicted it might be the Indonesian government's official
response to a call for an immediate deployment of a U.N.
peacekeeping force in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
Violence has flared up in East Timor since the announcement of
the August 30 ballot result by the United Nations on September 4.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian military declared a state of emergency in East
Timor on September 7, but violence has not been stopped
completely. Reports said more than 100 people have been killed and
tens of thousands of houses burned down.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations and some Western countries have urged the
Indonesian government to invite international forces to East Timor
for the restoration of security and order in the territory.
</P>
<P>
Indonesian Defense Minister and Commander of the Armed Forces
Gen. Wiranto said on Saturday in Dili, capital of East Timor, that
"Bearing in mind the international pressure for a zero-accident
rate in East Timor as soon as possible, we cannot rule out the
possibility of accelerating the arrival of the peacekeeping
force."
</P>
<P>
East Timor, a former Portuguese colony, was integrated into
Indonesia in 1976, but the move was never recognized by the United
Nations.  
</P>
</TEXT>
