<DOCNO> XIE19990912.0128 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania's Honeybee Exports Decline Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania's exports of
honeybee declined sharply last year but bee wax exports increased
slightly, according to an official with the Ministry of Natural
Resources and Tourism.
</P>
<P>
Honeybee exports in 1998/99 (from July 1 of 1998 to June 30 of
1999) plunged to 39 tons from 225 tons in 1997/98, with foreign
exchange earnings dropping from 275,000 U.S. dollars to 36,000
U.S. dollars, said Director for Natural Resources Philemon
Luhanjo.
</P>
<P>
Luhanjo told Sunday Observer earlier this week that honeybee
production had decreased for lack of serious efforts to promote
bee keeping in the country.
</P>
<P>
Contrary to the decrease of honey bee exports, bee wax exports
in the east African country arrived at 332 tons earning a foreign
exchange of 1.2 million U.S. dollars, compared with 316 tons worth
1 million U.S. dollars in the previous year, he said.
</P>
<P>
But he said the current output is far from enough as the
country is capable of producing 9,200 tons of bee wax every year.
</P>
<P>
Bee wax production in Tanzania, he said, had shrunk over the
past decades because of unreliable foreign market.
</P>
<P>
Between 1978 and 1982, Tanzania was the third among the18 bee
wax exporters in the world, following the Netherlands and Germany,
the official said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
