<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Strives to Turn Youth Into Skilled Manpower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Bangladeshi Prime Minister
Sheikh Hasina said Saturday that her government is working to turn
the country's youth into skilled manpower by giving them modern
and developed education.
</P>
<P>
If upgraded into skilled manpower, young people will play an
important role in building up the country's economy, Hasina told
the foundation-laying ceremony of Dinajpur Hajee Danesh Science
and Technology University, according to reports reaching here.
</P>
<P>
As part of its plan to establish science and technology
universities in 12 greater districts, the government has upgraded
Hajee Danesh Agriculture College into a full-pledged Science and
Technology University where agriculture will be a faculty.
</P>
<P>
It is the second science and technology university in the
country. The government plans to establish four more such
universities by 2002.
</P>
<P>
Hasina said the next century will be an era of science and
technology when every single person would have to compete for his
existence.
</P>
<P>
As there will be no alternative to science and technology based
education, the government wants to develop the huge population
into human resources by giving them education befitting to the
time, she noted.
</P>
<P>
Referring to her government's success in raising the country's
literacy rate, Hasina said that it is 58 percent as against 47
percent three years ago, adding that Bangladesh will be able to
free the nation from the course of illiteracy by the year 2006.
</P>
</TEXT>
