<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "My Heart Beats for China" (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 12 (Xinhua) -- In 1950, shortly after the
founding of the People's Republic of China, a beautiful foreign
lady could be seen on the streets of Beijing riding a bike with a
camera and from time to time aiming her lens at the hustle and
bustle of the lives of ordinary Beijingers.
</P>
<P>
Her exotic face seldom incurred impoliteness, other than a few
surprised glances. People usually cast friendly smiles her way,
smiles that remain forever on her photographs.
</P>
<P>
Today, this 88-year-old woman who is a Chinese citizen has the
tens of thousands of photos she took, a precious record reflecting
China in the 1950s and 1960s, showing the world how China has
changed since those days.
</P>
<P>
The German-born Eva became connected with China when, 65 years
ago, she and the well-known Chinese poet and Communist Xiao San
fell in love at their first glimpse in the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
In 1939, she arrived in Yan'an where she met Xiao's schoolmate
from Hunan Teacher's School, a man who was also the co-founder of
the progressive "Xinmin Society"-- Mao Zedong. It was at this time
and place when she first received a Chinese name -- Ye Hua.
</P>
<P>
The founding of New China excited the couple tremendously. "The
country everywhere was dynamic and seething with enthusiasm,"
recalled Ye," Clouds of flies that used to gather on the food sold
by peddlers gradually disappeared...it's hardly believable that
these neatly dressed and well-behaved children were once wild ones
covered with lice and begging along the streets...Many new operas
were staged in the theater..."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990912.0141 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
