<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "My Heart Beats for China" (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Ye even made it to Tibet, where she found that "vegetables
Tibetans never saw before were available, and children that couldn
't go to school before 1951 were seated in classrooms."
</P>
<P>
In the eyes of Ye Hua, a new world has emerged here, where
people are building a free and prosperous new China. "I could
hardly imagine it a couple of years ago," she said.
</P>
<P>
For half a century, Ye's fate was closely connected to that of
China. She enjoyed the glittering days endowed with love, but also
suffered hardships when she was imprisoned for seven years during
the turmoil of the Cultural Revolution (1966-76).
</P>
<P>
"I grow up along with the New China," she said in simple
Chinese. "If China is good, I am happy and, if China is bad, I am
painful."
</P>
<P>
"Now that five decades have passed, people are living a better
and happy life, they are better educated, and have more freedom to
do what they like," Ye said.
</P>
<P>
An idealistic and frank woman, Ye didn't hide her
dissatisfactions, saying that "I love China, that's why I greatly
minded those problems."
</P>
<P>
However, she added that "those problems will surely be overcome
as they are temporary phenomena during the country's step forward.
"
</P>
<P>
"China keeps changing for the better, and this is an
irreversible trend." Ye put her hand to her chest, and said, "I am
deeply rooted in China, my heart beats for China."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990912.0143 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "My Heart Beats for China" (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The elderly woman now lives in a building in western part of
Beijing which was built in the late 1970s to house ranking
officials and their family members. The building is now no longer
as attractive as it was, but has been almost swallowed by all the
high-rises now surrounding it.
</P>
<P>
A large photo in her room catches the eye: workers in plain
coats hurling chisels at the flagstones on a ground scattered with
stone filings. Behind, the Great Hall of the People with its rock
base laid out, from which the grand scale of the construction
would proceed.
</P>
<P>
Ye is still vigorous enough to work 10 hours a day, collecting
and indexing her photos and negatives, writing and corresponding.
Frequently, she finds herself on trips to foreign countries for
exhibitions and the publishing of her memoirs, one of which was
reprinted six times in Germany.
</P>
<P>
She published her autobiography abroad with the title "China,
My Dream, My Love," and has held photo exhibitions called "China,
Dream Come True" where she compared each photo to "a Chinese heart.
"
</P>
<P>
In one of her books, "Xiao San and I", Ye vowed to devote her
late years to the "great cause" her Chinese husband undertook as
his life career.
</P>
<P>
"Though World War II ended half a century ago, still many
places in the world are having wars and conflicts," she explained.
"That's why I shall continue my efforts to achieve peace between
people and people."
</P>
<P>
"China is peaceful all the time," she said, "and this comforts
me."  
</P>
</TEXT>
