<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Heavy Rains Affect Philippine Tobacco Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Nearly 17 million kilos of
tobacco have been lost due to the abnormal rains in March and
April, seriously affecting the Philippines' tobacco industry, the
National Tobacco Administration (NTA) said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The rains, which could be attributed to the La Nina and El Nino
phenomena, destroyed some 13.5 million kilos of Virginia tobacco,
and 3.5 million kilos of native tobacco and other tobacco, said
the NTA in a report released here.
</P>
<P>
"These losses constitute 21.59 percent of the total volume of
production for the current year 1998-99, adversely affecting
28,896 farmers or 46.3 percent of the total number of tobacco
farmers, covering an estimated 11,319.88 hectares or 28.1 percent
of the total area planted to tobacco," the report said.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the farmers who suffered from the El
Nino/La Nina-induced rains have been practically reduced to
marginal living. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
