<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two Britons Arrested for Illegal Presence in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Two Britons have been
arrested in Nandi District, Kenya's Western Province, for being
illegally in the country and engaging in dubious business
activities.
</P>
<P>
The Sunday Standard newspaper quoted Nandi police chief Francis
 Changwany as saying the two, a man and a woman (names withheld),
who were arrested Saturday, had engaged in business without
permits.
</P>
<P>
Changwany said the Britons, who claimed to represent a British
offshore international bank, were allegedly involving in a
money-lending business in Nandi Hill town. The male suspect also
masqueraded as a lawyer and doctor.
</P>
<P>
The suspects will be arraigned in court Monday, the police boss
said.
</P>
<P>
Changwany noted that drug-trafficking and other criminal
activities has increased sharply in the district, and he blamed
foreigners for the upsurge.
</P>
<P>
He urged all non-citizens in the district who are in the
country illegally to report to the police immediately.  
</P>
</TEXT>
