<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Multinational Peace Force in Southeastern Europe Opens Headquarters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, September 11 (Xinhua) -- The Multinational Peace Force
in Southeastern Europe (MPSEE) inaugurated its headquarters
Saturday afternoon in Plovdiv, the second largest city of Bulgaria
in the south.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the ceremony, Bulgarian President and Supreme
Commander-in-Chief of the Armed Forces, Peter Stoyanov, said the
inauguration of the first MPSEE headquarters in Bulgaria "is
fully in line with one of Bulgaria's major political external
priorities involving the establishment of good neighborly and
friendly relations among the countries in the region."
</P>
<P>
He said his country's efforts are focused on building a
peaceful and secure region and making it an integral part of a
united Europe in the future.
</P>
<P>
The president was confident that sooner or later Serbia and
other republics of former Yugoslavia will join the peace force.
</P>
<P>
He also voiced firm opposition to attempts to maltreat the Serb
population in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Chief of the MPSEE political-military supervisory committee
Nikolaos Dimadis, of Greece, described the day as historic, as it
symbolizes the member countries' resolve to set the beginning of a
new era in the region and to establish a system of security, peace
and cooperation.
</P>
<P>
MPSEE Commander Hilmi Akin Zorlu, of Turkey, inspected the
ranks. The national flags of the member-countries -- Albania,
Bulgaria, Greece, Italy, Macedonia, Romania and Turkey, were
hoisted to the seven countries' national anthems.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of the defense ministries and general staffs of
the seven member- countries, diplomats, military attaches
accredited to Bulgaria, representatives of the EU and NATO
attended the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Later in the day, Stoyanov cut the ribbon to inaugurate the
MPSEE headquarters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
