<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Film Wins Top Prize at Venice Film Festival </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 11 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese film "Not One Less"
directed by Zhang Yimou won the top Golden Lion prize at the 56th
Venice Film Festival on Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
The film tells the story of a substitute teacher in a Chinese
village who tried hard to bring back to school a boy unable to
attend classes any more. The jury of the festival said they were
deeply touched by the natural and sincere feeling displayed by a
cast of non-actors, most of them children.
</P>
<P>
The film is Zhang's second Golden Lion title at the Venice
Festival after he first won the prize seven years ago.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian film "The Wind Will Carry Us," directed by Abbas
Kiarostami, took the jury's special prize.
</P>
<P>
Best acting honors went to French actress Nathalie Baye in "A
Pornographic Liaison" and to Britain's Jim Broadbent for his role
in "Topsy-Turvy."
</P>
<P>
Some 120 films all over the world were shown at the festival
starting on September 1, with 18 of them competing for the Golden
Lion prize. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990912.0155 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Finance Ministers Meet in Finland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HELSINKI, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Finance ministers and
central bank governors of 15 European Union members discussed
regional economic prospects, the tax package deal and shortening
the double currency period during an informal meeting which began
on Saturday in Turku, Finland.
</P>
<P>
During the two-day meeting, which was also attended by
officials from the European Central Bank and the European Union
Commission, ministers and top bankers agreed that the economic
prospects of the 15-nation bloc are improving and that the status
of the euro is being enhanced.
</P>
<P>
Yyes-Thibault de Silguy, the European Union's commissioner for
economic and monetary affairs, said that the European Economic and
Monetary Union has had a good beginning and the euro has gained
the ability to shield the Union's members from global financial
storms.
</P>
<P>
The EU Commission forecast the economic growth of its members
for this year and next year will be 2 percent and 2.7 percent
respectively, Silguy said.
</P>
<P>
He also urged EU members to cut budget deficit and undertake
economic restructuring.
</P>
<P>
Ministers and bankers spent much time discussing the cut of
value-added tax (VAT) on service sectors for the creation of
thousands more job opportunities.
</P>
<P>
They reached agreement that EU governments could have a free
hand next year to start piloting on lowering VAT on two of the
following five labor-intensive, low-paid and community- based
services: hairdressing, small repairs of bicycles and shoes,
renovation of private housing, cleaning and home care.
</P>
<P>
The chair of the meeting, Finnish Finance Minister Sauli
Niinisto, hailed the agreement as being important and a good
signal for broader discussions on tax issue in the future.
</P>
<P>
On the contrary, ministers could not narrow their differences
over taxation on savings.
</P>
<P>
Britain fears a proposal supported by most other EU nations for
a 20 percent tax on interest from savings will hit the euro bond
market mostly based in London.
</P>
<P>
The proposal was also rejected by Luxembourg, which does not
tax foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
Niinisto said the ministers will wrap up a tax deal by a
December summit in Helsinki.
</P>
<P>
Participants of the meeting also agreed to shorten the double
currency period in most of the 11 euro countries from six months
to two months.
</P>
<P>
The Y2K (Year 2000) problem, relief funds in Kosovo and western
Balkans were also topics at the meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990912.0156 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
