<DOCNO> XIE19990912.0161 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil to Allow Foreign Oil Firms to Have Dollar Accounts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, September 11 (Xinhua) -- The National Monetary
Council (CMN), a branch of the Central Bank of Brazil in charge of
the country's monetary policy, will permit foreign firms operating
in the oil and energy fields to have accounts in dollars and other
foreign currencies in the national banking system.
</P>
<P>
CMN officials said Saturday that the decision will reduce the
pressure on the exchange market which comes from the demands for
dollars by foreign firms operating here.
</P>
<P>
Central Bank International Affairs Director Daniel Gleizer said
that for a start the permission will be limited to foreign firms
of the oil and energy sector, because they are the ones which
have the biggest need for hard currencies.
</P>
<P>
Gleizer told the O Globo newspaper that "projects in the oil
and energy areas take a long time to show results, so foreign
firms protect themselves against possible economic changes by
taking refuge in the dollar."
</P>
<P>
The official explained that for this reason, the CMN measure is
aimed at reinforcing foreign investor investment and reducing the
pressure on the foreign exchange market, which fluctuated badly
during past weeks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990912.0162 </DOCNO>
