<HEADLINE> Xinhua World Economic News Summary at 0500 GMT, September 12 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA -- Cyprus and Mauritius have initialed an agreement
which provides for the avoidance of double taxation, the Cyprus
News Agency (CNA) reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was sealed Thursday in Mauritius by Cyprus'
Finance Minister Takis Clerides, who is on a four-day visit to
Mauritius, and his Mauritius' counterpart. (Cyprus-Mauritius-
Accord)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The Labor Department reported Friday that prices
at the wholesale level rose 0.5 percent in August, mainly because
of a big jump in energy prices and a smaller gain in food costs.
</P>
<P>
The August's increase in the Producer Price Index followed a
modest 0.2 percent rise in July. It was worse than expected. Many
analysts had been anticipating that prices would rise 0.3 percent
in August. (US-Wholesale Prices)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA -- The Ethiopian Finance Ministry has reduced the
excise and sales taxes levied on beer and stout from 150 percent
to 50 percent, the Monitor newspaper reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The sales and excise rate was made effective as of August 7,
1999, but the factory-gate price of the various beers being
produced has not been adjusted yet, an unidentified source of beer
industry was quoted as saying. (Ethiopia-Tax Reduction)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
HELSINKI -- The two-day Forum on European Union (EU)
audiovisual policy ended here Friday after discussion on how to
protect European film and television industry from America's
superiority in this field.
</P>
<P>
The forum, held by Finland, which is holding the EU rotating
presidency, and Commission of the European Union, was attended by
over 200 exports from more than 30 European countries. (Finland-
Audiovisual-Forum)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
QUITO -- Ecuadorian President Jamil Mahuad said Saturday that
his government will practice austerity and budget discipline to
reactivate the economy of the country in the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
One of the government goals will be to reduce inflation from 55-
60 percent this year to 25-30 percent in search of a three percent
economic growth in 2000, said Mahuad during a week-end speech. (
Euador-Austerity)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ROME -- Italian Premier Massimo D'Alema Saturday opened the
63rd Trade and Industrial Fair of the southern Adriatic port of
Bari with an appeal to Italian entrepreneurs to take a more
courageous approach to business innovation.
</P>
<P>
According to Italian news agency Ansa, D'Alema told Italian
businessmen that the government was doing its part to boost
Italian economic growth but asked them to "give a more courageous
push in the direction of innovation in terms of products and
services offered." (Italy-Economy) 
</P>
</TEXT>
