<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese, Japanese Leaders Meet on Bilateral Relations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AUCKLAND, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President Jiang
Zemin and Japanese Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi held talks here
Sunday on relations between their two countries.
</P>
<P>
In the talks, Obuchi expressed his willingness to make greater
efforts for further promoting the development of Sino-Japanese
relations.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi said that Japan actively supports China's accession to
the World Trade Organization (WTO) at an early date.
</P>
<P>
As the 50th anniversary of the founding of the People's
Republic of China is approaching, Obuchi expressed his cordial
congratulations on China's achievements during the past 50 years.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on the same occasion, Jiang said that the development
of relations between China and Japan is generally in a favorable
momentum, but the two sides should make further efforts to
maintain this trend.
</P>
<P>
In particular, sensitive issues challenging the two countries
should be appropriately settled in the interests of the overall
bilateral relations, Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese president expounded to Obuchi China's positions on
its accession to the WTO and the issue of Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
He said China has noticed that the Japanese government
reaffirmed its persistence in the one-China policy and its policy
of not supporting Taiwan's independence immediately after Lee Teng-
hui dished out the "two-states" theory.
</P>
<P>
China hopes that Japan will strictly stick to its declared
positions and commitments made on the issue of Taiwan, he stressed.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, the two leaders also exchanged views on
issues of common concern.
</P>
<P>
The talks between Jiang and Obuchi were held ahead of the two-
day seventh informal meeting of leaders of the Asia-Pacific
Economic Cooperation (APEC) forum, which is scheduled to open here
later Sunday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
