<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Coal-bed Methane Co-development Proposed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 12 (Xinhua)-- China expects to speed up the
exploration of its coalbed methane (CBM) fields by beefing up its
co-operation with foreign firms, China Daily "Business Weekly"
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The China United Coalbed Methane Co Ltd (CUCBM) is negotiating
with several foreign partners to enhance overseas co-operation
after signing six contracts with four companies of the United
States, said Sun Maoyuan, vice-president of the corporation.
</P>
<P>
"The huge potential for coalbed methane development in China
has drawn wide international attention," Sun said.
</P>
<P>
The CUCBM will try to create a more favorable exploration
climate for foreign companies, he noted.
</P>
<P>
"We are asking relevant departments under the State Council to
simplify procedures and approve the blocks to be opened up for
foreign companies," Sun said. "We are also asking them to exempt
or reduce several taxes and fees such as the value-added tax,
income taxes and exploration permit fees."
</P>
<P>
The State Council has given the CUCBM exclusive right to
undertake the exploration, development and production of coalbed
methane in co-operation with overseas partners.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Government has approved the opening of nine coalbed
methane blocks for foreign co-operation. These are in the areas of
north and south of Huaihe River in Anhui, eastern areas of the
Taihang Mountains in North China, and Linxing, Sanjiao, North
Sanjiao, Shilou and Liulin areas in Shanxi, and Fengcheng of
Jiangxi.
</P>
<P>
Texaco Inc of the U.S. the first overseas company to join in
the project. It signed a contract with CUCBM on January 8, 1998,
in Beijing to jointly explore coalbed methane resources at the
Huaibei coal mine in Anhui.
</P>
<P>
On June 29, CUCBM wrapped up three contracts with Arco of the U.
S. to jointly develop coalbed methane resources in Sanjiao, North
Sanjiao and Shilou concessions in Shanxi. It also signed a
contract with Phillips, of the U.S., for the co-operative
development of coalbed methane in the Linxing concessions in
Shanxi.
</P>
<P>
On August 13, 1999, the CUCBM and SABA Petroleum Inc of the U.S.
signed a contract in Beijing to explore CBM resources in Fengcheng
of Jiangxi Province.
</P>
<P>
"The CUCBM is likely to sign three more contracts with foreign
companies late this year," said Fan Zhiqiang of the corporation.
</P>
<P>
CUCBM has mapped out seven targets for international
cooperation. Their exploration awaits approval of the State
Council, Fan said.
</P>
<P>
In addition to international cooperation, the CUCBM has decided
to set up its own coalbed methane development base in the Qinshui
basin of Shanxi, according to Sun.
</P>
<P>
With a total area of 550 sq km, Qinshui basin is expected to
produce 40-50 million cubic metres of coalbed methane annually
during the next two years.
</P>
<P>
China's coalbed methane reserves, estimated to about 30,000-
35000 billion cubic metres, are located about 2,000 metres
underground.
</P>
<P>
CUCBM would like to produce 3 billion cubic metres of CBM
annually by 2005, 10 billion cubic metres annually by 2010, and 20
billion cubic metres by 2015. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
