<HEADLINE> Andre Agassi Factfile </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Age: 29, Height: 5-feet-11-inches, Weight: 165 pounds, Plays:
Right-handed;
</P>
<P>
Career titles: 42;
</P>
<P>
Grand Slam singles titles: 4;
</P>
<P>
U.S. Open seeding: 2;
</P>
<P>
1987: won first ATP Tour title as a wild card entry in
Itiparica, Brazil;
</P>
<P>
1988: won six titles in seven finals, semi-finalist at French
Open and U.S. Open;
</P>
<P>
1989: won lone title of year in Orlando, Florida, runner-up in
Rome;
</P>
<P>
1990: runner-up at French Open and US Open, won inaugural ATP
Tour; world championships, won three other titles and helped U.S.
to Davis Cup victory over Australia;
</P>
<P>
1991: won titles in Orlando and Washington, runner-up French
Open;
</P>
<P>
1992: captured first Grand Slam title at Wimbledon, where he
beat three-time champions Boris Becker and John McEnroe; won
Toronto and Atlanta, led United States to Davis Cup title;
</P>
<P>
1993: won titles in San Francisco and Scottsdale; underwent
right wrist surgery in December;
</P>
<P>
1994: won U.S. Open for second Grand Slam singles title; won
four other titles, including Super Nine events in Toronto and
Paris, became first player to move from outside top 30 to finish
the year at number two in the world;
</P>
<P>
1995: won Australian Open for third Grand Slam singles title;
won career-high seven titles in 11 finals, compiled 73-9 match
record and claimed world number one ranking on April 10; held
number one ranking for 30 weeks; lost to Pete Sampras in U.S. Open
final;
</P>
<P>
1996: Won Super Nine titles in Key Biscayne and Cincinnati,
first player to win three Key Biscayne titles, won Olympic gold
medal in the Atlanta Games; held number one ranking for two weeks;
</P>
<P>
1997: failed to reach an ATP Tour final, Lost fourth round of U.
S. Open in only Grand Slam appearance of the year; fell to 141 in
world rankings, played two Challenger events, winning in Burbank;
</P>
<P>
1998: made biggest one-year jump in history of world rankings,
from 122 at end of 1997 to number six at end of 1998; reached 10
finals, won titles in San Jose, Scottsdale, Washington, Los
Angeles, Ostrava, compiled Tour-high 51 hardcourt victories, 11-2
on carpet, 5-3 on clay;
</P>
<P>
1999: won French Open to become the fifth man to complete a
career Grand Slam; won titles in Hong Kong and Washington, missed
a month of play with bursitis in his right shoulder, has lost to
only two players since his French Open run, Pete Sampras in the
Wimbledon final and Yevgeny Kafelnikov in the semi-finals at
Montreal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
