<HEADLINE> Clinton Congratulates Serena on Historic Grand Slam Win </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 11 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill
Clinton congratulated the newly-crowned U.S Open champion Serena
Williams on Sunday and extended his invitation to her and her
family for a victory celebration at the White House.
</P>
<P>
The 17-year-old American outlasted top-ranked Martina Hingis
from Switerland 6-3, 7-6 for the Open victory, giving herself a
grand slam title in only her second year as a pro and making her
the first black woman to win a Grand Slam tennis event since
fellow American Althea Gibson in 1958.
</P>
<P>
"This was an incredible tournament," Clinton was quoted by
White House spokesman Joe Lockhart as telling Williams by
telephone.
</P>
<P>
"What a great victory for you today," he said. "We are so
proud of you. I know your whole family must be happy for you."
</P>
<P>
Lockhart said Clinton had invited Williams and her family to
the White House for celebration. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
