<HEADLINE> Overseas Investors May Issue A or B Shares </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 12 (Xinhua) -- China will allow eligible
overseas-invested businesses to issue domestic currency A shares
or foreign currency B shares.
</P>
<P>
"Foreign-invested enterprises meeting the requirements can
apply to issue A or B shares," today's China Daily "Business
Weekly" quoted Ma Xiuhong, foreign trade minister assistant, as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Most companies listed in Shenzhen or Shanghai are controlled by
the state. Only a small number of them are private firms or
foreign-invested companies ahead of their initial public offerings
of A or B shares.
</P>
<P>
Few Chinese mainland-based companies in which foreign investors
held a 100 percent or a controlling stake have received approval
to issue shares to the public.
</P>
<P>
Ma told delegates to the China Fair for International
Investment and Trade that China would set up special industry
funds to help cash-short Chinese investors expand their stakes in
Sino-foreign joint ventures.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, it would allow domestic commercial banks to issue
loans to Chinese shareholders to increase capital in Sino-foreign
joint ventures, she said. 
</P>
