<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Materials Influence Rises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 12 (Xinhua) -- New materials is now
spreading into almost every aspect of modern Chinese life.
</P>
<P>
In the 1994-98 period, the industrial output of new materials
rose in value to 13.2 billion yuan (1.6 billion U.S. dollars), 34.
8 percent of the total high-tech yield, China Daily "Business
Weekly" reports today.
</P>
<P>
It also earned more than 100 million U.S. dollars in foreign
currency, representing as much as 47.6 percent of the high-tech
realm's total.
</P>
<P>
More than 400,000 people working in more than 1,000 enterprises
and nearly 500 research institutes and universities and colleges
in China are engaged in developing or manufacturing new materials
products.
</P>
<P>
China's Torch Plan Program, initiated to introduce high
technologies in industry, listed 395 new materials projects
between 1988 and 1994. This served as a guideline for the country'
s high-tech industry, and these programs accounted for 26.2
percent of 1,503 State programs during the period.
</P>
<P>
Partly as a result of governmental guidance and support, a
handful of new materials enterprises grew to become heavy weight
player in the market.
</P>
<P>
This is evident in the automobile, electronics and information
technology industries where new materials are heavily used and are
expected to form the basis for further development of the new
materials industry, industrial analysts said.
</P>
<P>
If 30 percent of the materials needed to build a car are new
materials, according to the experience of the United States auto
industry, and if China manufactures 1.5 million cars and 1.5
million other vehicles during 2000 as planned, the automobile
industry in 2000 could foster a new materials market valued at
more than 60 billion yuan (7.2 billion U.S. dollars).  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
