<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Electronic Exports Increase (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Despite hefty increases in
electronic exports, the sector is not doing as well as it should
be, today's China Daily "Business Weekly" reported.
</P>
<P>
A need for improved communications between electronics
manufacturers and trading houses has been cited.
</P>
<P>
Improved communications could help the industry become still
more competitive internationally.
</P>
<P>
According to an industry expert, exports of China's electronics
products during the first half of this year rose by 20.4 percent
from a year ago to 16.91 billion US dollars, accounting for 20.1
percent of exports during the same period.
</P>
<P>
Electronic exports are growing faster than any other export
item. Overall exports during the January-June period declined by 4.
6 percent to 83 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, electronic exports to Europe and the United States
are on the rise. More than 55 percent of the exports, worth 94.3
billion US dollars, were targeted at the EU and U.S. markets,
according to Chinese customs statistics.
</P>
<P>
The United States was the biggest target market with Chinese
electronic exports valued at 4.01 billion US dollars or 23.1
percent of Chinese electronic exports.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong and Japan ranked second and third after the U.S., and
the Japan-bound electronic exports during the period were 2.22
billion US dollars, making up 13.1 percent of electronic exports
during the January-June period.
</P>
<P>
The processing trade played a dominant role in the export of
electronic products.
</P>
<P>
Chinese customs statistics indicated that importing raw
materials for export-oriented processing and processing with
customers' materials, worth 15.24 billion US dollars, were factors
in 90.1 percent of the electronic exports during the first six
months of this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990912.0186 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Electronic Exports Increase (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Although processing trade contributes a lot to employment
opportunities and the foreign exchanges earnings of the country,
its shortcomings should not be ignored, the expert said.
</P>
<P>
He went on to say that the processing trade is easily affected
by fluctuations in exchanged rates on international financial
markets. It is a destabilizing factor in the pricing of electronic
exports and affects their competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
The processing trade is little concerned with China's
electronic industry and helps little in upgrading the industry and
optimizing its industrial structure.
</P>
<P>
Consequently, the technological content of electronic exports
has increased only marginally during the past few years. As a
result most of the exports were of low-grade and possessed low
added value,newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
Core technologies are controlled by foreign companies and there
are very few high-tech Chinese electronic firms of relatively-
large scale.
</P>
<P>
The prices of most electronic exports are low, which limits the
potential for expanding such exports because of thin profit margin.
</P>
<P>
In addition, a lack of common interests between Chinese
electronic manufacturers and trading houses undermines the
competitiveness of such exports.
</P>
<P>
Most of the manufacturers, which acquired foreign trading
rights over the past 10 years, are paying large "tuitions" to
learn to how to explore the world electronic markets.
</P>
<P>
Most of the trading houses, ignored by the manufacturers, are
pulling away from the electronic products exporting businesses and
taking decades of professional experience with them.
</P>
<P>
To eradicate snags cutting into the competitiveness of Chinese
electronic exports, the experts suggested the country should
commit itself to developing high-tech and high value-added
electronic products and encourage the co-operation between
industrial firms and trading houses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
