<HEADLINE> Workshop on Health Care Management Held in Myanmar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, September 12 (Xinhua) -- A workshop on quality
management in health care is being held here to improve managerial
capability and performance of local health officials and
administrators.
</P>
<P>
The three-day workshop, which began Saturday, is sponsored by
the Myanmar Ministry of Health and the Bumrungrad Hospital of
Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar has been making efforts to realize the goal of "health
for all" by the year 2000 with primary health care as the key
approach since the Alma-Ata declaration in 1978.
</P>
<P>
The country's national health policy reaffirms the provision of
equitable health care, accessibility with universal coverage,
multi-sectoral and community involvement.
</P>
<P>
In line with the policy, a hospital care program has been
formulated, with special attention given to the availability and
affordability of drug and health care services for people living
in remote rural areas.
</P>
<P>
In addition, a community health care program has also been
worked out with emphasis on provision of basic health services,
maternal and child health care and education regarding nutrition
through the primary health care approach.
</P>
<P>
There are 734 hospitals, 350 dispensaries, 1,410 rural centers
and 348 maternal and child health care centers in Myanmar with
14,007 doctors, 11,840 nurses and 9,524 midwives. 
</P>
</TEXT>
