<HEADLINE> Tianjin Strives to Be Industrial Base in Northeast Asia (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Tianjin Municipality in north
China has been growing from a domestic industrial city into an
international industrial base, Mayor Li Shenglin said today when
discussing the city's prospects for the 21st Century.
</P>
<P>
Looking back at the great changes that have occurred in Tianjin
since the founding of new China in 1949, Li said the city's
industrial growth has gone through two stages: one in the 1960s,
when modern industry emerged; and the other after the
implementation of reform and opening-up policy two decades ago.
</P>
<P>
Eleven industrial areas were set up at the outskirts of the
city after 1949, and a compact industrial system was established
when a group of key factories, including the Dagang Oilfield Group
Limited Company, the Tianjin Oil Refinery, the Tianjin Automobile
Works, and the Tianjin Watch Factory were set up one after another.
</P>
<P>
The total industrial output value in 1978 reached 15.79 billion
yuan (about 189.5 million U.S. dollars), 24-fold more than in 1949.
</P>
<P>
Since 1978 the municipality has been turning into an
international port city, and also a production base in northeast
Asia. The total industrial output value last year was as much as
256.2 billion yuan, 13.6 times that of 1978.
</P>
<P>
Li added that in the past few years, Tianjin has benefited
enormously from the reform of its existing industries.
</P>
<P>
More than four billion U.S. dollars of overseas investment has
been used over the past five years to overhaul large and medium-
sized state-owned enterprises, which has helped them upgrade their
technological level to the world standard.
</P>
<P>
And 200 of the first 500 multinationals have up to now set up
branches or agencies in Tianjin, with that investment exceeding
eight billion U.S.dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
