<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibetans Eat More Fresh Fruit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Residents of Lhasa, the capital
of China's Tibet Autonomous Region, eat an average 10,000 kg of
fruit daily, statistics from the city's commerce department show.
</P>
<P>
A fruit wholesaler told Xinhua that more than 20 kinds of
fruits, including Lichi from Hainan Province and the Guangxi
Zhuang Autonomous Region in south China, watermelon and grapes
from northwest China's Gansu Province and the Xinjiang Uygur
Autonomous Region, and even fruit from the United States, Thailand
and Latin America, are sold in Lhasa.
</P>
<P>
A decade ago, fresh fruit was regarded as a luxury in Tibet.
Now fruit sales are brisk in Lhasa and the price is comparatively
low, the vendor said.
</P>
<P>
This year's sales volume of imported fruit to Lhasa is expected
to double over last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
