<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Latvian Wins Paris-Brussels Cycling Classic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Latvia's Romans Vainsteins
outsprinted Switzerland's Beat Zberg to take the 260-kilometer
Paris-Brussels cycling classic on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Zberg, who rode for Italy's Vini Caldirola team, became the
first Latvian winner of the race as he chalked up a winning time
of five hours and 59 minutes.
</P>
<P>
After both breaking away from the pack, Zberg launched the
decisive attack with about 18 kms left, but Vainsteins quickly
caught him and the two riders took turns at the front.
</P>
<P>
With about 200 meters left, Vainsteins seized his chance and
left Zberg in his wake to take the victory, adding to his
successes this year including winning a stage of the Giro d'Italia
in May.
</P>
<P>
Two of the race favorites, Belgium's Johan Museeuw and Italy's
Mirko Celestino, chose the famous Alsemberg hill, about 36 kms
from the finish, for a break. But their efforts turned out to be
a failure. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
