<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Serena Williams Beat Hingis for U.S. Open Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Serena Williams claimed
historic Grand Slam win as she outlasted Martina Hingis in two
sets to capture the title of the U.S. Open tennis championships in
New York on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Williams dominated most of the game for a 6-3, 7-6 (7-4)
victory, giving the 17-year-older a title in only her second year
as a pro and making herself the first black woman to win a Grand
Slam champion since fellow American Althea Gibson in 1958.
</P>
<P>
Williams controlled the rhythm until late in the second set
when top seeded Hingis , who has beat twice Serena's older sister
Venus Williams in the U.S. Open, managed to keep herself in the
game and pressured Williams liable to mistakes.
</P>
<P>
But Serena clawed back into the game and sent the thriller to a
tiebreak before she claimed the victory on her third match point
of the day as Hingis was long with a backhand lob.
</P>
<P>
The victory means the Americans will capture both singles
titles. Earlier Saturday, Todd Martin routed Frenchman Cedric
Pioline 6-4, 6-1, 6-2 to set up an all U.S. final, against fellow
American Andre Agassi.
</P>
<P>
Agassi did his part by rallying from a first-set debacle to
beat Yevgeny Kafelnikov 1-6, 6-3, 6-3, 6-3. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
