<DOCNO> XIE19990912.0206 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Urges Halt to Violence in East Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 11 (Xinhua) -- China demanded
Saturday that all forms of violence in East Timor be stopped
immediately and the security of U.N. personnel there be protected.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Permanent Representative to the U.N. Qin Huasun made
the statement at a Security Council debate on East Timor following
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan's appeal to Indonesia for
accepting a multi-national peace-keeping force for East Timor.
</P>
<P>
Appreciating U.N.'s efforts for the smooth conducting of the
ballot on East Timor's future, which turned to be in favor of
independence, the envoy said China hopes that the ballot outcome
will be fully implemented in a peaceful and orderly environment.
</P>
<P>
China is gravely concerned over the continuing violence and
resulting humanitarian crisis in East Timor, hoping that the
measures taken by the Indonesian Government will achieve desirable
results as soon as possible, Qin said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the issue of East Timor must be solved through
the United Nations and the deployment of any peace-keeping force
should be at the request of the Indonesian Government and endorsed
by the Security Council.
</P>
<P>
"China is willing to be actively involved in efforts by the
U.N. in this connection," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990912.0207 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Rejects Outside Military Action in E. Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia on Saturday
reiterated its position of rejecting an international military
force for East Timor.
</P>
<P>
Indonesian Ambassador to the U.N. Makarim Wibisono told the
Security Council that Indonesia does not see the need of such a
force at the moment.
</P>
<P>
"My government, while fully understanding the willingness of a
number of countries to provide security assistance to Indonesia,
does not foresee the need for the introduction of a
multi-national, or a peace-keeping force at this stage," he said.
</P>
<P>
The envoy said for now indonesia's imposition of martial law on
September 7 was already helping improve the security situation in
the territory, the former Portuguese colony annexed by Indonesia
in 1976 after Portugals' withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
"Such an operation may well exacerbate the situation and be
counter-productive, however well-intentioned it may be," he said.
</P>
<P>
The idea of sending a multi-national force to East Timor was
raised by U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan Friday as he saw the
security situation there deteriorating.
</P>
<P>
Many countries expressed their support to the idea at the
council's debate and the discussions would be resumed as soon as
the council's mission to Jakarta returns next week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
